#robertkime #robertkimedesign #london
Today’s sunshine on a very chilly Thursday. Good morning from Ebury Street.

At this time of year, a little moment of red 📍 from a project in the Bahamas. Creating a room within a larger room with wall hangings, a light bedcover, and the structure of the antique four poster. The white bolsters give a freshness. That is the balance. 
.
#robertkime #robertkimedesign

In the midst of all the snow, a plant room of Robert’s in a page from ‘The English Garden Room’ by Elizabeth Dickson. 
.
#robertkime

As we often say - the rising tide lifts all the boats. In this case, an interesting wooden model boat, which arrived this summer and is now at Ebury Street. From our photo shoot last week, an interesting (+ intriguing) piece. 
.
#robertkime

The pattern. A Syrian inlaid hardwood settee, C 1850 that has just arrived at Ebury Street. This past summer, Robert spoke of inlaid furniture, suggesting to us: “It is not about the outline. It’s about the pattern. And the people making these inlaid pieces felt pattern was far more important to them. Broadly, an inlaid pattern was an attitude to them.”

A most beautiful half tester has arrived at the showroom. The detailed hangings lined, silk fringes and embroidery patterns reworked + restored. It appealed for the original work involved in creating it. 18th C Italian. Wonderful colours. An important piece in a room, with the scale of the design. And so to bed.
A very long, rustic table. Antique chairs with colourful seats, mixed dinner services, and a single candle. The season is here.

A wooden model of the Duomo di Milano has arrived at Ebury Street. Detailed and quite beautiful, as is the cathedral itself, which took nearly six centuries to complete, fully (1386–1965). Good things are worth waiting for.
A Happy Christmas to all.

These quiet days. 
.
Christmas to the new year.
Happy New Year. Thank you. And hello to 2023.

We’ve been thinking + talking about fabric lampshades lately. What they add to a room and perhaps even why they can be so interesting. Long a staple in a Kime interior, Orlando Atty explains “how a beautiful lampshade adds a missing layer, how it can even bring a room together” suggesting it as “one of the many things Robert taught us all”. More on the story with Claire Jackson too. Letting the light in.

The kitchen, as absolutely part of the plan. The • Reading Lamp • with its bright shade is given room to tuck in. A lovely London project. 
.
#robertkimedesign #robertkime
A place to put everything, a lovely, long table and cheering chairs…on a walk through Ebury Street, on the way to the garden.

Sometimes a larder, often a place to arrange wild or garden blooms - an ancient stone sink at Robert’s La Gonette. Spring is ahead. And then summer and on it goes.

One of the things that Robert always commented upon when speaking about Swangrove was that they really didn’t buy anything for the project - other than fabrics. Instead, they rooted in the attics and stores of Badminton finding all the things that became the bones of this project, giving it the structure.
Here, a set of dining chairs got loose covers, with a short, pleated frill (not too tight or exact) made from old French linen sheets, which lightened the mood of the dining room.
One enters on the ground floor;  Swangrove is a belvedere and as such, the rooms are stacked, with this room on the lowest level. The door, slightly ajar, gives this away. 
.
#swangrove #robertkimedesign

NARA Ii is the second chapter of fabrics and wallpapers to join The Nara Collection that launched in May 2020. The Nara Collection marks a collaboration and friendship which first solidified over Robert Kime’s interior design projects at Tory Burch and her husband Pierre-Yves Roussel’s home in Normandy, France. The designs are inspired by a journey the late Robert Kime and Tory Burch took to Japan in 2019.
Nara, an ancient city and home to some of Japan’s oldest temples, shrines, and ruins, lends its name to the collection. On their journey, Robert, Tory, and Orlando Atty spent time exploring cities and the surrounding landscapes, learning about the area’s history and rich culture.
.
#naracollection #robertkime

From @simonuptonphotos new book, ‘London Living’ a Robert Kime project in London is paired with the owner’s contemporary house in the country in a chapter titled Acquiring Minds. In text written by the client, a key sensibility and aim of the work is detailed - “that I love the room I am in at any given time.”

A satisfying outcome for us. Swipe to see some images from the book.

Our story with ikats has a new chapter today. Introducing three new designs, developed by Orlando with the artistan weavers in Turkey that have been making the Robert Kime ikats for many years - “I like using them on cushions, for lampshades and upholstery too. Made in the traditional method, by hand, on looms - what someone might initially see as a flaw, is character and makes them more interesting.” 
Swipe to welcome: Afyon, Kasan + Medina.

Making a case for pale walls, painted beams + dining chairs (a set of more than a dozen) slipcovered in heavy white cloth fashioned from old French flour sacks. The dining room at Swangrove - a hunting lodge, or maison de plaisance, built in 1703 for the second Duke of Beaufort on the edge of his estate, Badminton Park. 
The architect William Killigrew designed it with fantastical rooflines and, between steeply-pitched gables, he gave it an attic room – a belvedere or observatory – with windows on two sides.

Keeping the bauble tradition going - Robert’s collection of old Egyptian coloured glass baubles was well loved. A perfect, unusual gift - a colourful bauble; a little bit old, a little bit new. At Robert Kime.
